<br>
XP is ok.  At least it doesn't leak memory like 98 and below, but it's got problems all over the place.  Once it breaks at one point, the whole system goes down hill from there.  (Not like linux where you break one thing and the rest of the computer stays up as if nothign happened.  Actually I've only had under 10 hard crashes of a linux computer I owned ever.  I put down my win2k computer at least 6 times yesterday alone.)  Plus XP has compatiblity issues left and right, but hey, it can't be worse than 98.<br>
<br>
There will be a XP SE, but it could be a year or 2.  I don't think Longhorn is scheduled till like 2004 or 2006.  And I agree w/ everyone here, don't upgrade, take the kick in the beanbag and do the work to do a good, clean format and install.  Your going to a completely different kernel (frame work of the OS) with XP and it's not going to mix well w/ the rest of your system if the rest of your system still wants to fit in the 98 framework.<br>
<br>
As for me?  This summer I'm going to buy a completely up to date and new computer and run Mandrake linux 8.2 and KDE 3 on it.  Honestly, I do 75% of my computing on my linux computer now.  All my web browsing, networking, schduleing, mailing, etc.  I only use my windows computer for things that don't come for linux or are just too powerful for the slow system I have (400mhz k6-2 w/ 128 sdram and 10gig hdd).<br>
<br>
I do most of my gaming on my windows computer along with most of my word processing.  I honestly don't like kword that much.  It really isn't that great and it doesn't read word documents worth a damn which is something I need.  There are other linux office sets available that I haven't tried.  There is open office, star office (the new version isn't free but I might buy it if it gets good reviews), another office I can't remember, and Codeweavers (a company that publishes software to run windows software on linux computers) has released a program that will run microsoft office on a linux computer.  Apperenlty Word, Excel, and Powerpoint run splendidly.  The software isn't complete yet though.  IE, and outlook have signifigant problems I understand.  But a refreshing thing is that Codeweavers sais up front exactly what will work and exactly what won't.  The review I read started with, "Don't bother reading this review because what Codeweavers said would and wouldn't work is exactly what did and didn't."  Plus Codeweavers promises many updates for those who purchase the 1.0 version so that they aren't left w/ partially functioning software.<br>
<br>
Codeweavers also produces the crossover plugin which runs things like quicktime, flash, microsoft media player, RA, etc on a linux computer though xmms (kinda like winamp though winamp 3 has a linux version also) can handle many of the non-propritary standards.  As for games, well that is definately lacking, but companies do make linux games.  Quake is always released with a linux version, I think CS might have a linux version.  Wine (runs windows programs, many times games, on linux) 2.0 was just released with full capabilities to run Jedi Knight 2.   You can buy a version of mandrake that actually comes with the sims and I believe Civ is produced for linux, so there are a lot of major games that can be played on a linux box.<br>
<br>
And I think alot of professional software is starting to be produced for linux.  My brother works heavily with 3D animation and modeling software and apperently that whole sector will have mitigated to linux some time in the next couple of years.  For me, I know I run MATLAB on my linux computer though I'm not sure what other pieces of engineering software are available for linux.<br>
<br>
So Really if you can get Win2k, do.  If you have 98 and can't get 2k, get XP but do a completely clean install.  And if you are daring, just go to linux.  Both mandrake and Suse are designed to run either beside or in windows so you should be able to share the space on your machine, (though I've never done it.)  Plus the formerly Redmond Linux (forget the name now) supposeably has a great installation and Lindows (linux with a LARGE amount of support for windows applications, primarily through very advanced modifications to Wine) will be out soon.<br>
<br>
Oh, and as for BMW's, my father had a BMW Z3 roadster convertable, (I know, not a Z5 but he isn't exactly independantly wealthy).  That thing was the sharpest, most precise car I've ever driven.  You wouldn't believe it cornering, handling, accellerating, etc.  (One time I took a right corner at 40mph.  I slid over 1 lane but it was hellafun.)  But you put that thing on even the most slightly wet road and it was like driving on glass ice.  Had ZERO traction.  Father actually totaled it that way, hit a wet spot and was thrown off the road.  Met Mr Tree.<br>
<br>
But thats just my opinion. <p>--------------------------
